# [SML](../wg/sml.html)

## Summary

The SML Working Group met at IETF 126. The session focused on resolving open issues in the core structured email draft (`draft-ietf-sml-structured-email`) and discussing the newly adopted structured quoted content draft (`draft-ietf-sml-structured-quoted-content`). Key debates centered on the technical placement of structured data within messages (separate MIME parts versus embedding in HTML), handling client-side replacement of HTML content, and establishing flags or headers to signal Machine Readable Messages (MRMs). Due to time constraints, the scheduled presentation on trust and security considerations (`draft-ietf-sml-trust`) was deferred.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Structured Email (Core Draft)
The presenter of the core draft introduced updates to [Structured Email (Core draft)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-sml-structured-email-core-draft-02) for `draft-ietf-sml-structured-email`, focusing on Section 4 (placement and content types) and Section 6.

*   **Placement of Structured Data (HTML vs. Separate MIME Parts):**
    *   The draft previously recommended clean, separate MIME parts and discouraged embedding structured data within HTML (legacy practice). 
    *   Arndt noted that implementation experience shows that some client codebases find it easier to insert JSON-LD as HTML comments, while others prefer separate MIME parts, suggesting both should be allowed.
    *   Philip proposed a distinction based on use cases: separate MIME parts are appropriate for fully machine-readable messages to save bandwidth, while embedding within HTML is highly logical for partial representations where the structured data and HTML are tightly coupled semantically.
    *   Ben Books argued for a fourth category of data—"information about the message content" (such as structured quotes)—which inherently belongs inside the HTML. He proposed putting JSON-LD directly into HTML attributes, noting that HTML attributes are far more likely to survive replying and forwarding loops (e.g., between Apple Mail and Outlook) than separate MIME parts or `<script>` tags.
    *   The Working Group agreed to take the discussion of this "fourth class" of data placement to the mailing list.

*   **Signed/Encrypted JSON-LD (JOCEY):**
    *   The core draft mentions using JOCEY standards (JSON Web Signatures) for signing/encrypting structured data. The presenter suggested aligning this section with `draft-ietf-sml-trust`.

*   **Subject Line Warnings:**
    *   The presenter proposed warning against placing critical structured data only in the subject line of a Machine Readable Message (MRM). Alexey recommended changing any strict "must not" language to a softer encouragement to ensure readability for automated and human receivers.

*   **HTML Rendering & Replacement:**
    *   The draft includes a `data-id` attribute to link HTML elements with concepts in the structured data.
    *   The presenter introduced hints for "presentation deepness" (brief vs. detailed representations, e.g., in newsletters).
    *   Arndt previously proposed a way to suppress HTML fallbacks so a client could render its own view from the structured data. The presenter proposed a `data-load-replace` parameter to indicate that an HTML element is designed to be replaced by client-rendered content.
    *   Neil Jenkins raised security concerns regarding client-side HTML injection. He argued that standard mechanisms like `multipart/alternative` or `multipart/mixed` should be used instead of injecting content into HTML. Ben Books countered that secure rendering (such as using iframes) is client-implementation-specific. The security implications of HTML replacement will be discussed on the mailing list.

*   **MRM Flags and Headers:**
    *   The draft defines an IMAP/SMTP flag for Machine Readable Messages (MRM) and a general "has structured data" flag.
    *   Philip pointed out that IMAP flags are set by receivers, leaving senders with no way to signal that a message is an MRM. He proposed introducing a sender-side header to signal MRM status and adding a registry of valid sub-types (e.g., one-time codes or vacation notices) so MUAs can make better decisions.
    *   DKG suggested that flags should be evaluated based on practical client utility (e.g., optimization or message list displays) rather than purely conceptual consistency.

