### 2. Structured Quoted Content
Philip presented [Structured Quoted Content](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-sml-structured-quoted-content-01) for `draft-ietf-sml-structured-quoted-content`.

*   **Draft Updates:**
    *   The draft has been adopted by the working group.
    *   Support for plain text was dropped to simplify the draft, as target MUAs generally support HTML.
    *   A `forward preamble` property was added to capture client-inserted forwarding headers.
    *   Examples covering forwarding/reply chains, inline comments, and legacy quoting were added.
    *   Dropping plain text resolved complex inline attachment concerns; attachments are now handled using standard HTML image references.

*   **Open Issues & Feedback:**
    *   **Back-referencing:** Philip noted the difficulty of finding a feasible way to reference exactly which segment of an original message is being quoted. Ben Books agreed this is highly complex and likely unfeasible.
    *   **Vocabulary:** Philip raised concerns about mixing schema.org and custom SML vocabularies. The presenter of the core draft confirmed this is standard, acceptable practice in RDF/JSON-LD.
    *   **Property Definitions:** Alexey requested that the draft explicitly list and define supported properties in a table (including missing CC and BCC recipient fields) and specify client behavior when encountering unknown properties.
    *   **HTML blockquote and cite attribute:** Ben Books noted that Netscape and Thunderbird historically used `<blockquote cite="cid:...">` to reference quoted messages, which was highly effective. He asked how the IETF could work with the WHATWG/W3C to standardize this. Neil Jenkins clarified that the `cite` attribute is already valid HTML for blockquotes and accepts URLs; thus, the WG only needs to define a valid URL scheme (e.g., mid/cid) rather than changing the HTML specification.

